In article &lt;2764@medusa.informatik.uni-erlangen.de&gt; eckert@medusa.informatik.uni-erlangen.de (Toerless Eckert) writes:

&gt;From article &lt;1608@mcsun.eu.net&gt;, by dfk@eu.net (Daniel Karrenberg):
&gt;&gt; Just include all data even for hosts and sites without connectivity.

&gt;No, it's a design decision

 And a bad one to IMHO.

&gt;This way we can have different MX records in the DE zone in the states,
&gt;and the german one.

 So the design is based on a division of the world in
 1) USA, 2) Germany and 3) unimportant (unmentioned) Fringe.

&gt;(surely nearly the same effect can be reached by adding more MX records
&gt;to one zone, but then you might end up sending mail from germany to germany
&gt;through the states, if something is not running correctly,
&gt;something which happens rather often around here)

 The goal should be: optimal functionality for sites that set up
 things properly. It always takes a little effort to get a named
 going smoothly. Complicating things doesn't help in general.

&gt;Anyway, i don't see the need for discussion here:

 You will always evoke discussion when you complicate matters for odd reasons.

&gt;it doesn't make a difference for anyone that the zones are different,

 I'm doing things correctly and end up sending (some) mail from
 the Netherlands to Germany through the states. I haven't heard
 a convincing argument why this should be so.
